{"title_page": "F\u00e9lix Sellier", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = F\u00e9lix Sellier\n| image         = Aangereden door een auto - Hit by a car.jpg\n| full_name     = F\u00e9lix Sellier\n| nickname      = le minneur\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1893|01|02}}\n| birth_place   = [[Spy, Belgium|Spy]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1965|04|16|1893|01|02}}\n| death_place   = [[Gembloux]], Belgium\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = Paris\u2013Brussels (1922, 1923, 1924)<br/>Paris\u2013Roubaix (1925)<br/> Belgian National Road Race Champion<br/>3 stages Tour de France\n}}\n\n'''F\u00e9lix Sellier''' ([[Spy, Belgium|Spy]], 2 January 1893 \u2013 [[Gembloux]], 16 April 1965) was a [[Belgium|Belgian]] professional [[road bicycle racer]].\n\n==Stage victory in 1921 Tour de France==\nIn the [[1921 Tour de France]], the cyclists were separated in two classes, the sponsored riders and the unsponsored riders. For the thirteenth stage, these classes started separated, partly because the Tour organisers wanted to punish the sponsored riders for not attacking the leader [[L\u00e9on Scieur]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1921.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=15\u00e8me Tour de France 1921|language=French|accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> and partly because the leader in the second class was helped by cyclists in the first class.<ref name=\"lenaars\">{{cite web|url=http://www.henkleenaers.nl/fiets12.htm|title=Vergeten Tour-winnaar uit Tongeren|author=Henk Leenaers|accessdate=17 June 2009|publisher=Fiets|year=2003|language=Dutch}}</ref> Sellier was one of the riders in the second class, and therefore could start two hours earlier than the favourites. Some of the second class cyclists including Sellier stayed ahead, and Sellier managed to win the stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1921_13.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=15\u00e8me Tour de France 1921 \u2013 13\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French|accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> Sellier would finish 8th overall of the second class cyclists, and 16th in the overall combined classification.\n\nIn the next year, Sellier started the [[1922 Tour de France|Tour de France]] as sponsored cyclist. He again won a stage, but this time he had started at the same time as everybody else. He finished the race in third place.\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1912\n:Binche-Tournai-Binche\n;1919\n:[[Tour of Belgium]] (independents)\n;1920\n:Marchienne-au-Pont\n:Mellet\n:Moustier\n;1921\n:Jemeppe-Bastogne-Jemeppe\n:[[1921 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 13\n;1922\n:[[1922 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 14\n::3rd overall classification\n:[[Paris\u2013Brussels]]\n:Arlon-Oostende\n;1923\n:Criterium du midi\n: {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Belgian National Road Race Championships]]\n:Paris\u2013Brussels\n;1924\n:Gembloux\n:Oupeye\n:[[Paris-Lyon]]\n:[[Tour of Belgium]]\n:Paris\u2013Brussels\n;1925\n:Gembloux\n:GP de soissons\n:[[1925 Paris\u2013Roubaix|Paris\u2013Roubaix]]\n;1926\n: {{flagicon|BEL}} Belgian National Road Race Championships\n:[[1926 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 4\n;1927\n:Gembloux\n;1928\n:Six days of Brussels (with [[Henri Duray]])\n:St. Servais\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cycling Archives|5591}}\n*[http://histo.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/1967.html Official Tour de France results for F\u00e9lix Sellier]\n\n{{Belgian National Road Race Championships (men)}}\n{{Paris\u2013Roubaix winners}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sellier, Felix}}\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Belgian Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Namur (province)]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Jemeppe-sur-Sambre]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = F\u00e9lix Sellier\n| image         = Aangereden door een auto - Hit by a car.jpg\n| full_name     = F\u00e9lix Sellier\n| nickname      = le minneur\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1893|01|02}}\n| birth_place   = [[Spy, Belgium|Spy]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1965|04|16|1893|01|02}}\n| death_place   = [[Gembloux]], Belgium\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = Paris\u2013Brussels (1922, 1923, 1924)<br/>Paris\u2013Roubaix (1925)<br/> Belgian National Road Race Champion<br/>3 stages Tour de France\n}}\n\n'''F\u00e9lix Sellier''' ([[Spy, Belgium|Spy]], 2 January 1893 \u2013 [[Gembloux]], 16 April 1965) was a [[Belgium|Belgian]] professional [[road bicycle racer]].\n\n==Stage victory in 1921 Tour de France==\nIn the [[1921 Tour de France]], the cyclists were separated in two classes, the sponsored riders and the unsponsored riders. For the thirteenth stage, these classes started separated, partly because the Tour organisers wanted to punish the sponsored riders for not attacking the leader [[L\u00e9on Scieur]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1921.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=15\u00e8me Tour de France 1921|language=French|accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> and partly because the leader in the second class was helped by cyclists in the first class.<ref name=\"lenaars\">{{cite web|url=http://www.henkleenaers.nl/fiets12.htm|title=Vergeten Tour-winnaar uit Tongeren|author=Henk Leenaers|accessdate=17 June 2009|publisher=Fiets|year=2003|language=Dutch}}</ref> Sellier was one of the riders in the second class, and therefore could start two hours earlier than the favourites. Some of the second class cyclists including Sellier stayed ahead, and Sellier managed to win the stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1921_13.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=15\u00e8me Tour de France 1921 \u2013 13\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French|accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> Sellier would finish 8th overall of the second class cyclists, and 16th in the overall combined classification.\n\nIn the next year, Sellier started the [[1922 Tour de France|Tour de France]] as sponsored cyclist. He again won a stage, but this time he had started at the same time as everybody else. He finished the race in third place.\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1912\n:Binche-Tournai-Binche\n;1919\n:[[Tour of Belgium]] (independents)\n;1920\n:Marchienne-au-Pont\n:Mellet\n:Moustier\n;1921\n:Jemeppe-Bastogne-Jemeppe\n:[[1921 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 13\n;1922\n:[[1922 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 14\n::3rd overall classification\n:[[Paris\u2013Brussels]]\n:Arlon-Oostende\n;1923\n:Criterium du midi\n: {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Belgian National Road Race Championships]]\n:Paris\u2013Brussels\n;1924\n:Gembloux\n:Oupeye\n:[[Paris-Lyon]]\n:[[Tour of Belgium]]\n:Paris\u2013Brussels\n;1925\n:Gembloux\n:GP de soissons\n:[[1925 Paris\u2013Roubaix|Paris\u2013Roubaix]]\n;1926\n: {{flagicon|BEL}} Belgian National Road Race Championships\n:[[1926 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 4\n;1927\n:Gembloux\n;1928\n:Six days of Brussels (with [[Henri Duray]])\n:St. Servais\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cycling Archives|5591}}\n*[http://histo.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/1967.html Official Tour de France results for F\