{"title_page": "Eva Channing", "text_new": "'''Eva Channing''' (1854-1930) was a Boston area [[suffragist]] leader and writer. \n\n== Private Life ==\nEva Channing was born in 1854 to parents [[William Francis Channing]] and Susan Elizabeth Burdick Channing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://documents.alexanderstreet.com/d/1009657343|title=Biographical Sketch of Eva Channing {{!}} Alexander Street Documents|website=documents.alexanderstreet.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Her mother was also active in the suffrage movement, and her grandfather, [[William Ellery Channing]], was a well-known Unitarian minister.<ref name=\":0\" /> Eva Channing attended Boston University as a member of the class of 1877.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Career ==\nChanning served in a number of Boston area suffrage organizations, including the [[Massachusetts Woman Suffrage Association]] and the Massachusetts School Suffrage Association.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition, she wrote frequent contributions to the ''Women's Journal,'' advocating for women's rights in both Europe, particularly Germany, and the United States.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Channing, Eva}}\n\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:American suffragists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n[[Category:19th-century American women]]\n", "text_old": "'''Eva Channing''' (1854-1930) was a Boston area [[suffragist]] leader and writer. \n\n== Private Life ==\nEva Channing was born in 1854 to parents William Francis Channing and Susan Elizabeth Burdick Channing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://documents.alexanderstreet.com/d/1009657343|title=Biographical Sketch of Eva Channing {{!}} Alexander Street Documents|website=documents.alexanderstreet.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Her mother was also active in the suffrage movement, and her grandfather, William Ellery Channing, was a well-known Unitarian minister.<ref name=\":0\" /> Eva Channing attended Boston University as a member of the class of 1877.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Career ==\nChanning served in a number of Boston area suffrage organizations, including the [[Massachusetts Woman Suffrage Association]] and the Massachusetts School Suffrage Association.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition, she wrote frequent contributions to the ''Women's Journal,'' advocating for women's rights in both Europe, particularly Germany, and the United States.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Channing, Eva}}\n\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:American suffragists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n[[Category:19th-century American women]]\n", "name_user": "Susanc1906", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Wikipedia links for family members", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eva_Channing"}
{"title_page": "Micro-series", "text_new": "{{tone|date=July 2018}}\nA '''micro-series''' (also microseries) is a very short [[Episode|episodic]] [[television program]]ming \nnarrative sponsored by an [[advertiser]]. This is a non-traditional way of reaching primary markets. A micro-series is intended to promote a product while engaging viewers with entertaining content. These episodes are generally two to three minutes long and often run during commercial breaks of popular television programs. After each air date, they are also available online and on mobile devices.\n\n== Popular micro-series ==\nEven if it doesn't have a wide audience, a micro-series creates buzz, especially if it is interactive, as in the case of CBS's 2006 micro-series ''[[The Courier (micro-series)|The Courier]]''.\nSometimes a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] micro-series is created from a popular TV show, for example, [[NBC]]'s prime-time hit, ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''. In November 2008, [[Sprint Nextel]] sponsored a four-episode micro-series called Heroes: Destiny on mobile, online and television. Each five- to seven-minute episode debuted on Monday nights. The micro-series featured Sprint's {{Not a typo|Instint}}<!--This word is spelled correctly--> phone in some scenes in what David Lang, head of [[MindShare]] Entertainment, calls \"subtle integration.\" Sprint ads also aired adjacent to the on-air promos.<ref name=adweek>{{cite web |url=http://www.adweek.com/aw/content_display/news/agency/e3i2d029babe3flf02e891f425f76dbf63a |publisher=Ad Week |title=''Mindshare Preps 'Heroes' Microseries''}}</ref>\n\nIt is important that the micro-series content fits the environment or theme of the program in which it airs. A good example of this is [[TBS (TV network)|TBS]]'s micro-series ''Commuter Confidential''. In 2008, TBS debuted a two-minute episode of ''Commuter Confidential'' featuring [[Revlon]] products and [[Match.com]], during ''[[Sex and the City]]''. The micro-series plotline mirrors the comedy of the [[HBO]] produced ''Sex and the City''. ''Confidential'' features four female characters and their diverse ways of dealing with the world around them.<ref name=promomagazine>{{cite web |url=http://promomagazine.com/entertainmentmarketing/tbs_slots_revlon_matchcom_0602/ |publisher=Promo Magazine |title=''TBS Slots Revlon Match.com Micro-Series in Sex'' |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606051834/http://promomagazine.com/entertainmentmarketing/tbs_slots_revlon_matchcom_0602/ |archivedate=2008-06-06 }}</ref>\n\nWith the advent of the digital video recording ([[Digital video recorder|DVR]]), advertisers are trying to create brand messages that defeat the fast-forward button.  [[General Motors]] is sponsoring a five-part micro-series, ''My Manny'' on [[Turner Broadcasting]]'s TBS to highlight the features on its new Traverse Crossover vehicle. It airs during the original series ''[[Tyler Perry's House of Payne]]''.<ref name=brandfreak>{{cite web |url=http://www.brandfreak.com/2009/01/full-speed-ahead-for-the-chevy-traverse-in-new-tbs-microseries.html |publisher=Brand Freak|title=''Full Speed Ahead for the Chevy Traverse in new TBS microseries''}}</ref>\n\nWith the success of the ''My Manny'' series \u2013 now in its third season \u2013 General Motors sponsored a new series, ''[[Gillian in Georgia]]'', which aired on TBS in the spring of 2010. The show stars Jill Marie Jones of ''Girlfriends'' fame and centers around a hip New Yorker who comes to the South to live with her sister's family. The show airs during TBS\u2019 popular sitcom ''[[Meet the Browns (TV series)|Meet the Browns]]''.<ref name=tbs>{{cite web |url=http://news.turner.com/article_display.cfm?article_id=5122 |publisher=TBS|title=''TBS Unveils Newest Microseries GILLIAN IN GEORGIA, Presented by Chevy Malibu''}}</ref>\n\n[[Unilever]], too has gotten into the micro-series action. Singer [[Alicia Keys]] was selected by [[Dove]] and [[MTV]] to star in their \"real beauty\" micro-series called ''Fresh Takes''. The series revolves around a group of twentysomething females and the pressures they must overcome in order to pursue their dreams. Each mini series aired as a commercial intersitials during the March 24, 2008 premiere of ''[[The Hills (TV series)|The Hills]]''. The micro-series is intended to promote the new Dove products while confronting the issues of the self-esteem.<ref name=brownsista>{{cite web|url=http://brownsista.com/alicia-keys-fresh-takes-micro-series/|publisher=Brown Sista|title=''Alicia Keys' Fresh Takes Microseries''}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nSometimes a micro-series may turn into a half-hour television sitcom, as in the case of ''[[In the Motherhood]]'', a series of online shorts about moms coping with their chaotic lives \u2013 with help from Spring Nextel services and [[Suave]] hair care products. This micro-series just got picked up for the midseason lineup on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. It will anchor a new comedy block on Thursdays, one of the most competitive nights of TV.<ref name=brandfreak />\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Television genres]]\n", "text_old": "{{tone|date=July 2018}}\nA '''micro-series''' (also microseries) is a very short [[Episode|episodic]] [[television program]]ming \nnarrative sponsored by an [[advertiser]]. This is a non-traditional way of reaching primary markets. A micro-series is intended to promote a product while engaging viewers with entertaining content. These episodes are generally two to three minutes long and often run during commercial breaks of popular television programs. After each air date, they are also available online and on mobile devices.\n\n== Popular micro-series ==\nEven if it doesn't have a wide audience, a micro-series creates buzz, especially if it is interactive, as in the case of CBS's 2006 micro-series ''[[The Courier (micro-series)|The Courier]]''.\nSometimes a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] micro-series is created from a popular TV show, for example, [[NBC]]'s prime-time hit, ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]''. In November 2008, [[Sprint Nextel]] sponsored a four-episode micro-series called Heroes: Destiny on mobile, online and television. Each five- to seven-minute episode debuted on Monday nights. The micro-series featured Sprint's {{Not a typo|Instint}}<!--This word is spelled correctly--> phone in some scenes in what David Lang, head of [[MindShare]] Entertainment, calls \"subtle integration.\" Sprint ads also aired adjacent to the on-air promos.<ref name=adweek>{{cite web |url=http://www.adweek.com/aw/content_display/news/agency/e3i2d029babe3flf02e891f425f76dbf63a |publisher=Ad Week |title=''Mindshare Preps 'Heroes' Microseries''}}</ref>\n\nIt is important that the micro-series content fits the environment or theme of the program in which it airs. A good example of this is [[TBS (TV network)|TBS]]'s micro-series ''Commuter Confidential''. In 2008, TBS debuted a two-minute episode of ''Commuter Confidential'' featuring [[Revlon]] products and [[Match.com]], during ''[[Sex and the City]]''. The micro-series plotline mirrors the comedy of the [[HBO]] produced ''Sex and the City''. ''Confidential'' features four female characters and their diverse ways of dealing with the world around them.<ref name=promomagazine>{{cite web |url=http://promomagazine.com/entertainmentmarketing/tbs_slots_revlon_matchcom_0602/ |publisher=Promo Magazine |title=''TBS Slots Revlon Match.com Micro-Series in Sex'' |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080606051834/http://promomagazine.com/entertainmentmarketing/tbs_slots_revlon_matchcom_0602/ |archivedate=2008-06-06 }}</ref>\n\nWith the advent of the digital video recording ([[Digital video recorder|DVR]]), advertisers are trying to create brand messages that defeat the fast-forward button.  [[General Motors]] is sponsoring a five-part micro-series, ''My Manny'' on [[Turner Broadcasting]]'s TBS to highlight the features on its new Traverse Crossover vehicle. It airs during the original series ''[[Tyler Perry's House of Payne]]''.<ref name=brandfreak>{{cite web |url=http://www.brandfreak.com/2009/01/full-speed-ahead-for-the-chevy-traverse-in-new-tbs-microseries.html |publisher=Brand Freak|title=''Full Speed Ahead for the Chevy Traverse in new TBS microseries''}}</ref>\n\nWith the success of the ''My Manny'' series \u2013 now in its third season \u2013 General Motors sponsored a new series, ''[[Gillian in Georgia]]'', which aired on TBS in the spring of 2010. The show stars Jill Marie Jones of ''Girlfriends'' fame and centers around a hip New Yorker who comes to the South to live with her sister\u2019s family. The show airs during TBS\u2019 popular sitcom ''[[Meet the Browns (TV series)|Meet the Browns]]''.<ref name=tbs>{{cite web |url=http://news.turner.com/article_display.cfm?article_id=5122 |publisher=TBS|title=''TBS Unveils Newest Microseries GILLIAN IN GEORGIA, Presented by Chevy Malibu''}}</ref>\n\n[[Unilever]], too has gotten into the micro-series action. Singer [[Alicia Keys]] was selected by [[Dove]] and [[MTV]] to star in their \"real beauty\" micro-series called ''Fresh Takes''. The series revolves around a group of twentysomething females and the pressures they must overcome in order to pursue their dreams. Each mini series aired as a commercial intersitials during the March 24, 2008 premiere of ''[[The Hills (TV series)|The Hills]]''. The micro-series is intended to promote the new Dove products while confronting the issues of the self-esteem.<ref name=brownsista>{{cite web|url=http://brownsista.com/alicia-keys-fresh-takes-micro-series/|publisher=Brown Sista|title=''Alicia Keys' Fresh Takes Microseries''}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nSometimes a micro-series may turn into a half-hour television sitcom, as in the case of ''[[In the Motherhood]]'', a series of online shorts about moms coping with their chaotic lives \u2013 with help from Spring Nextel services and [[Suave]] hair care products. This micro-series just got picked up for the midseason lineup on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. It will anchor a new comedy block on Thursdays, one of the most competitive nights of TV.<ref name=brandfreak />\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Television genres]]\n", "name_user": "Dewritech", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePopular micro-series:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micro-series"}
{"title_page": "Adenomatoid tumor", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Adenomatoid tumor\n| synonyms        = \n| image           = Adenomatoid tumour -b- very high mag.jpg\n| caption         = High-magnification [[micrograph]] of an adenomatoid tumor. [[H&E stain]].\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Adenomatoid tumor''' is a [[benign]] [[mesothelial]] [[tumor]], which arises from the lining of organs. It generally presents in the genital tract, in regions such as the [[testis]]<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors =Williams SB, Han M, Jones R, Andrawis R |title=Adenomatoid tumor of the testes |journal=Urology |volume=63 |issue=4 |pages=779\u201381 |year=2004 |pmid=15072910 |doi=10.1016/j.urology.2003.11.035}}</ref> and [[epididymis]].<ref name=\"titleAdenomatoid tumor of the epididymis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gfmer.ch/selected_images_v2/detail_list.php?cat1=6&cat3=139&stype=d |title=Adenomatoid tumor of the epididymis |accessdate=2007-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615013911/http://www.gfmer.ch/selected_images_v2/detail_list.php?cat1=6&cat3=139&stype=d |archivedate=2007-06-15 }}</ref> It is the second most common extratesticular scrotal mass, after lipoma, and accounts for 30% of these masses.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cassidy|first1=Fiona Hughes|last2=Ishioka|first2=Kevin M.|last3=McMahon|first3=Colm J.|last4=Chu|first4=Pauline|last5=Sakamoto|first5=Kyoko|last6=Lee|first6=Karen S.|last7=Aganovic|first7=Lejla|title=MR Imaging of Scrotal Tumors and Pseudotumors|journal=RadioGraphics|date=May 2010|volume=30|issue=3|pages=665\u2013683|doi=10.1148/rg.303095049|pmid=20462987}}</ref> It also has been found in the [[pancreas]].<ref name=\"titleModern Pathology - Adenomatoid Tumor of the Pancreas: A Case Report with Comparison of Histology and Aspiration Cytology\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Overstreet K, Wixom C, Shabaik A, Bouvet M, Herndier B |title=Adenomatoid tumor of the pancreas: a case report with comparison of histology and aspiration cytology |journal=Mod. Pathol. |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=613\u20137 |date=Jun 2003|pmid=12808068 |doi=10.1097/01.MP.0000072803.37527.C8 }}</ref>\n\nIn the female, it has been found in the body of the [[uterus]] and the [[fallopian tube]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors =Huang CC, Chang DY, Chen CK, Chou YY, Huang SC |title=Adenomatoid tumor of the female genital tract |journal=Int J Gynaecol Obstet |volume=50 |issue=3 |pages=275\u201380 |date=Sep 1995|pmid=8543111 |doi= 10.1016/0020-7292(95)02453-J}}</ref>\n\n==Additional images==\n[[File:Adenomatoid_epidi_0001.jpg|thumb|left|Adenomatoid tumour of the epididymis]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| ICD10           = \n| ICD9            = \n| ICDO            = 9054/0\n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| MeshID          = D018254\n| SNOMED CT       = 2348006\n}}\n{{Soft tissue tumors and sarcomas}}\n\n[[Category:Benign neoplasms]]\n\n\n{{neoplasm-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Adenomatoid tumor\n| synonyms        = \n| image           = Adenomatoid tumour -b- very high mag.jpg\n| caption         = High-magnification [[micrograph]] of an adenomatoid tumor. [[H&E stain]].\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Adenomatoid tumor''' is a [[benign]] [[mesothelial]] [[tumor]], which arises from the lining of organs. It generally presents in the genital tract, in regions such as the [[testis]]<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors =Williams SB, Han M, Jones R, Andrawis R |title=Adenomatoid tumor of the testes |journal=Urology |volume=63 |issue=4 |pages=779\u201381 |year=2004 |pmid=15072910 |doi=10.1016/j.urology.2003.11.035}}</ref> and [[epididymis]].<ref name=\"titleAdenomatoid tumor of the epididymis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gfmer.ch/selected_images_v2/detail_list.php?cat1=6&cat3=139&stype=d |title=Adenomatoid tumor of the epididymis |accessdate=2007-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615013911/http://www.gfmer.ch/selected_images_v2/detail_list.php?cat1=6&cat3=139&stype=d |archivedate=2007-06-15 }}</ref> It is the second most common extratesticular scrotal mass, after lipoma, and accounts for 30% of these masses.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cassidy|first1=Fiona Hughes|last2=Ishioka|first2=Kevin M.|last3=McMahon|first3=Colm J.|last4=Chu|first4=Pauline|last5=Sakamoto|first5=Kyoko|last6=Lee|first6=Karen S.|last7=Aganovic|first7=Lejla|title=MR Imaging of Scrotal Tumors and Pseudotumors|journal=RadioGraphics|date=May 2010|volume=30|issue=3|pages=665\u2013683|doi=10.1148/rg.303095049|pmid=20462987}}</ref> It also has been found in the [[pancreas]].<ref name=\"titleModern Pathology - Adenomatoid Tumor of the Pancreas: A Case Report with Comparison of Histology and Aspiration Cytology\">{{cite journal |vauthors =Overstreet K, Wixom C, Shabaik A, Bouvet M, Herndier B |title=Adenomatoid tumor of the pancreas: a case report with comparison of histology and aspiration cytology |journal=Mod. Pathol. |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=613\u20137 |date=Jun 2003|pmid=12808068 |doi=10.1097/01.MP.0000072803.37527.C8 }}</ref>\n\nIn the female, it has been found in the body of the [[uterus]] and the [[fallopian tube]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors =Huang CC, Chang DY, Chen CK, Chou YY, Huang SC |title=Adenomatoid tumor of the female genital tract |journal=Int J Gynaecol Obstet |volume=50 |issue=3 |pages=275\u201380 |date=Sep 1995|pmid=8543111 |doi= 10.1016/0020-7292(95)02453-J}}</ref>\n\n==Additional images==\n[[File:Adenomatoid_epidi_0001.jpg|thumb|left|Adenomatoid tumour of the epididymis]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB     =  \n|  ICD10          =  \n|  ICD9           =  \n|  ICDO           = 9054/0 \n|  OMIM           =  \n|  MedlinePlus    =  \n|  eMedicineSubj  =  \n|  eMedicineTopic =  \n|  MeshID         = D018254\n}}\n{{Soft tissue tumors and sarcomas}}\n\n[[Category:Benign neoplasms]]\n\n\n{{neoplasm-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenomatoid_tumor"}
{"title_page": "A Place to Bury Strangers", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = A Place to Bury Strangers\n| image               = A Place To Bury Strangers.JPG\n| caption             =\n| image_size          =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| genre               = {{flatlist| \n*[[Noise rock]]\n*[[post-punk revival]]\n*[[shoegaze]]\n*[[experimental rock]]\n*[[psychedelic rock]]\n*[[space rock]]\n}}\n| years_active        = 2003\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist| \n*Killer Pimp\n*[[Rocket Girl]]\n*[[Mute Records]]\n*[[Dead Oceans]]\n}}\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist| \n*Skywave\n*MOFO\n*My Best Fiend\n*[[the D4]]\n*Black Acid\n*Ceremony\n}}\n| website             = {{url|https://aplacetoburystrangers.bandcamp.com/}}\n| current_members     = [[Oliver Ackermann]]<br />[[Dion Lunadon]]<br />Lia Simone Braswell\n| past_members        = David Goffan<br />Tim Gregorio<br />Jonathan \"Jono Mofo\" Smith<br />Jason \"Jay Space\" Weilmeister<br />Justin Avery<br />Robi Gonzalez<br />John Fedowitz\n}}\n\n'''A Place to Bury Strangers''' are a [[New York City]]-based American [[noise rock]] band, composed of [[Oliver Ackermann]] (guitar/vocals, bass), [[Dion Lunadon]] (bass guitar, guitar) and Lia Simone Braswell (drums). The band, commonly known by the initials APTBS, play a heavy, atmospheric [[wall of sound]]-influenced blend of [[psychedelic rock]], [[shoegaze]] and [[space rock]].\n\n==History==\n===Early days===\nA Place to Bury Strangers were formed in 2002 by David Goffan and Tim Gregorio. Current frontman and guitarist Ackermann had moved to New York following the disbanding of his previous group, Skywave, to join APTBS, and become the primary songwriter after the departure of Goffan. They played their first show at Luxx in [[Brooklyn]] in 2003. Jason \"Jay Space\" Weilmeister and Jonathan \"Jono Mofo\" Smith, both from the New York City-based band Mofo, joined the band when Gregorio left. In 2006, APTBS self-released three different EPs, handmade with different color schemes: ''Breathe'', ''Missing You'' and ''Never Going Down''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/A-Place-To-Bury-Strangers-A-Place-To-Bury-Strangers/release/3749678 |title=A Place To Bury Strangers - A Place To Bury Strangers (Vinyl, LP, LP) at Discogs |website=Discogs.com |date=2008-11-03 |accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, APTBS gained acclaim following their [[Webster Hall]] performance with [[the Brian Jonestown Massacre]]. The band returned to Webster Hall in 2007 to play with one of their major influences, [[the Jesus and Mary Chain]]. Throughout these formative years, the band's live shows became increasingly chaotic, which earned them the title of New York City's \"loudest band\" from various indie reviewers and bloggers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011213254/http://www.sonicfrontiers.net/php/show-11.html|title=A Place to Bury Strangers: 2007-09-20: Show Review|date=October 11, 2007|website=Web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://brainwashed.com/common/htdocs/discog/pimpk004.php?site=pimp |title=A Place To Bury Strangers |website=Brainwashed.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref> as well as \"the most ear-shatteringly loud garage/shoegaze band you'll ever hear\" by ''[[The Washington Post]]''.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120919121810/http://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn?node=cityguide/profile&id=1139889&categories=Music+Events&venueid=795685] {{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' applauded their revival of \"the ominous, feedback-drenched drones of the 1980s\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/22/arts/music/22cmj.html?ref=arts |title=Play Well, and May the Blog Buzz Be With You|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===First album and touring===\nIn 2007, Jon Whitney from the Killer Pimp label wrote the contract for their first album, ''[[A Place to Bury Strangers (album)|A Place to Bury Strangers]]'', on a napkin. In August 2007, the band gained national attention after a favorable ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' review of this album.\n\nIn 2007, the band joined [[Black Rebel Motorcycle Club]] on the \"Holy Fuck\" tour.<ref>[http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/46102-a-place-to-bury-strangers-open-for-brmc] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115145951/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/46102-a-place-to-bury-strangers-open-for-brmc|date=January 15, 2008}}</ref> In April 2008, it was announced that APTBS would open for [[Nine Inch Nails]] on several dates of the latter's US tour. Following several UK gigs, the first album was issued in the UK in October 2008 by [[Rocket Girl]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Maher|first=Dave|title=A Place to Bury Strangers Expand Tour|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/30123-a-place-to-bury-strangers-expand-tour/|website=Pitchfork.com|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> and they received strong praise from the British media including  ''[[NME]]'' and ''[[Kerrang!]]''. In November 2008, the band returned to Europe and the UK on tour supporting [[MGMT]].\n\n===''Exploding Head''===\nIn early 2009, APTBS signed to [[Mute Records]]. The band also announced another European tour and appearances at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]], [[Seaport Music Festival]] and [[Siren Music Festival]].\n\nTheir second album, ''[[Exploding Head]]'', was released by Mute in October 2009.\n\nIn spring 2010, Smith decided to leave APTBS for personal reasons rather than participate in their US tour supporting [[the Big Pink]]. He was replaced for that spring tour by Lunadon, formerly of the bands [[the D4]] and the True Lovers. On July 5, 2010, APTBS visited [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]] for the first time, and played at [[Rock al Parque]], the largest free rock festival in South America.\n\n===''Worship''===\nOn February 14, 2011, Ackermann stated that the band had begun working on their third full-length album.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.rockedition.com/interviews/interview-with-oliver-ackermann-of-a-place-to-bury-strangers |title=Interview with Oliver Ackermann of A Place To Bury Strangers |website=Rockedition.com |date=2011-02-14 |accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref> On January 10, 2012, A Place to Bury Strangers released an all-[[Hipstamatic]] video shot on an [[iPhone]] for the song \"So Far Away\" from the ''Onwards to the Wall'' EP. On February 12, 2012, the band announced that Robi Gonzalez had replaced Weilmeister as drummer.<ref>{{cite web|title=School of Seven Bells Remix A Place To Bury Strangers|url=http://deadoceans.com/blog/2012/02/school-of-seven-bells-remix-a-place-to-bury-strangers/|publisher=Dead Oceans|access-date=2012-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511050055/http://deadoceans.com/blog/2012/02/school-of-seven-bells-remix-a-place-to-bury-strangers/|archive-date=2012-05-11|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> On May 2, 2012, it was announced that the band's third album, ''[[Worship (A Place to Bury Strangers album)|Worship]]'', was scheduled for release on the [[Dead Oceans]] label, on June 11 in the UK and Europe and on June 26, 2012 in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/45996-a-place-to-bury-strangers-announce-new-album |title=A Place to Bury Strangers Announce New Album &#124; News |website=Pitchfork.com |date=2012-04-02 |accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref> The band announced plans to support the release with a full North American tour in October 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. Tour |url=http://aptbs.tumblr.com/ustourdates/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121130070353/http://aptbs.tumblr.com/ustourdates/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-11-30 |publisher=APTBS |accessdate=2015-03-26 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===''Strange Moon'' and ''Transfixiation''===\nIn early March 2013, APTBS announced that they had recorded covers of songs by [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] band [[Dead Moon]] for release on [[Record Store Day]] 2013 as an EP titled ''Strange Moon''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadoceans.com/blog/2013/03/aptbs-announce-tour-dates-with-japandroids-set-to-release-dead-moon-covers-ep-for-rsd/ |title=APTBS Announce Tour Dates with Japandroids, Set to Release Dead Moon Covers EP for RSD News |publisher=Dead Oceans |date=2013-03-06 |accessdate=2015-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324024120/http://deadoceans.com/blog/2013/03/aptbs-announce-tour-dates-with-japandroids-set-to-release-dead-moon-covers-ep-for-rsd/ |archive-date=2015-03-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Gonzalez decided to retire from touring, and during the subsequent 2016 tour, John Fedowitz (Skywave, Ceremony) played drums for the band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/aplacetoburystrangers/photos/a.334259118246/10153482309508247/?type=3|title=A Place To Bury Strangers|website=Facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, the band began recording their fourth studio album, ''Transfixiation''. They recorded for several days at ABC Studios in [[Etne]], [[Norway]], with [[Emil Nikolaisen]] of [[Serena Maneesh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=no&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&eotf=1&u=http%3A%2F%2Fgaffa.com%2Fartikkel%2F70113&authuser=0 |title=Google Translate |website=Translate.google.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref> The album was released on February 17, 2015 on Dead Oceans.\n\n===''Pinned''===\nIn February 2018, the band announced that Lia Simone Braswell would be a permanent replacement for Gonzalez as the band's drummer.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Place to Bury Strangers Release New Single \"Never Coming Back\"|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/01/a-place-to-bury-strangers-new-album-pinned-never-coming-back-stream/|website=Spin|accessdate=23 February 2018|date=31 January 2018}}</ref> Their fifth studio album, ''Pinned'', was released on April 13.\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[A Place to Bury Strangers (album)|A Place to Bury Strangers]]'' (2007, Killer Pimp)\n* ''[[Exploding Head]]'' (2009, [[Mute Records]])\n* ''[[Worship (A Place to Bury Strangers album)|Worship]]'' (2012, [[Dead Oceans]])\n* ''Transfixiation'' (2015, Dead Oceans)\n* ''Pinned'' (2018, Dead Oceans)\n\n===EPs===\n* ''Breathe'' (2006, self-released)\n* ''Missing You'' (2006, self-released)\n* ''Never Going Down'' (2006, self-released)\n* ''The Box Set'' (2008, Vacancy Records)\n* ''Hoxton Square Sessions'' (2009, Mute Records)\n* ''Ego Death 2010 Tour EP'' (2010, Mute Records)\n* ''[[Onwards to the Wall]]'' (2012, Dead Oceans)\n* ''Strange Moon'' (2013, Dead Oceans)\n\n===Singles===\n* \"To Fix the Gash in Your Head\" 10\"/12\" (2008, Meal Deal Records)\n* \"I Know I'll See You\" 7\" (2008, Rocket Girl/Vacancy Records)\n* \"Breathe\" 7\" (2008, Vacancy Records)\n* \"Missing You\" 7\" (2008, Rocket Girl/Vacancy Records)\n* \"[[In Your Heart]]\" 7\" (2009, Mute Records)\n* \"Keep Slipping Away\" 7\" (2009, Mute Records)\n* \"You Are the One\" 7\" (2012, Dead Oceans)\n* \"And I'm Up\" 7\" (2012, Dead Oceans)\n* ''Less Artists More Condos Series #1'' split single with Ceremony (2012, Famous Class)\n* \"Raiser\" 7\" (2013, Sweet Mistakes Productions)\n* \"We've Come So Far\" 7\" (2015, self-released)\n* \"Straight\" 7\" (2015, self-released)\n* \"Never Coming Back\" (2018, Dead Oceans)\n* \"There's Only One of Us\" (2018, Dead Oceans)\n\n===Live albums===\n* ''Loud and Live in 2012'' (2013, self-released)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://aplacetoburystrangers.bandcamp.com/}}\n\n{{A Place to Bury Strangers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Place To Bury Strangers}}\n[[Category:American noise rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Indie rock musical groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:Mute Records artists]]\n[[Category:Post-punk revival music groups]]\n[[Category:Shoegazing musical groups]]\n[[Category:Dead Oceans artists]]\n[[Category:Rocket Girl artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = A Place to Bury Strangers\n| image               = A Place To Bury Strangers.JPG\n| caption             =\n| image_size          =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| genre               = {{flatlist| \n*[[Noise rock]]\n*[[post-punk revival]]\n*[[shoegaze]]\n*[[experimental rock]]\n*[[psychedelic rock]]\n*[[space rock]]\n}}\n| years_active        = 2003\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist| \n*Killer Pimp\n*[[Rocket Girl]]\n*[[Mute Records]]\n*[[Dead Oceans]]\n}}\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist| \n*Skywave\n*MOFO\n*My Best Fiend\n*[[the D4]]\n*Black Acid\n*Ceremony\n}}\n| website             = {{url|https://aplacetoburystrangers.bandcamp.com/}}\n| current_members     = [[Oliver Ackermann]]<br />[[Dion Lunadon]]<br />Lia Simone Braswell\n| past_members        = David Goffan<br />Tim Gregorio<br />Jonathan \"Jono Mofo\" Smith<br />Jason \"Jay Space\" Weilmeister<br />Justin Avery<br />Robi Gonzalez<br />John Fedowitz\n}}\n\n'''A Place to Bury Strangers''' are a [[New York City]]-based American [[noise rock]] band, composed of [[Oliver Ackermann]] (guitar/vocals, bass), [[Dion Lunadon]] (bass guitar, guitar) and Lia Simone Braswell (drums). The band, commonly known by the initials APTBS, play a heavy, atmospheric [[wall of sound]]-influenced blend of [[psychedelic rock]], [[shoegaze]] and [[space rock]].\n\n==History==\n===Early days===\nA Place to Bury Strangers were formed in 2002 by David Goffan and Tim Gregorio. Current frontman and guitarist Ackermann had moved to New York following the disbanding of his previous group, Skywave, to join APTBS, and become the primary songwriter after the departure of Goffan. They played their first show at Luxx in [[Brooklyn]] in 2003. Jason \"Jay Space\" Weilmeister and Jonathan \"Jono Mofo\" Smith, both from the New York City-based band Mofo, joined the band when Gregorio left. In 2006, APTBS self-released three different EPs, handmade with different color schemes: ''Breathe'', ''Missing You'' and ''Never Going Down''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/A-Place-To-Bury-Strangers-A-Place-To-Bury-Strangers/release/3749678 |title=A Place To Bury Strangers - A Place To Bury Strangers (Vinyl, LP, LP) at Discogs |website=Discogs.com |date=2008-11-03 |accessdate=2015-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, APTBS gained acclaim following their [[Webster Hall]] performance with [[the Brian Jonestown Massacre]]. The band returned to Webster Hall in 2007 to play with one of their major influences, [[the Jesus and Mary Chain]]. Throughout these formative years, the band's live shows became increasingly chaotic, which earned them the title of New York City's \"loudest band\" from various indie reviewers and bloggers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011213254/http://www.sonicfrontiers.net/php/show-11.html|title=A Place to Bury Strangers: 2007-09-20: Show Review|date=October 11, 2007|website=Web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://brainwashed.com/common/htdocs/discog/pimpk004.php?site=pimp |title=A Place To Bury Strangers |website=Brainwashed.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref> as well as \"the most ear-shatteringly loud garage/shoegaze band you'll ever hear\" by ''[[The Washington Post]]''.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120919121810/http://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn?node=cityguide/profile&id=1139889&categories=Music+Events&venueid=795685] {{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' applauded their revival of \"the ominous, feedback-drenched drones of the 1980s\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/22/arts/music/22cmj.html?ref=arts |title=Play Well, and May the Blog Buzz Be With You|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===First album and touring===\nIn 2007, Jon Whitney from the Killer Pimp label wrote the contract for their first album, ''[[A Place to Bury Strangers (album)|A Place to Bury Strangers]]'', on a napkin. In August 2007, the band gained national attention after a favorable ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' review of this album.\n\nIn 2007, the band joined [[Black Rebel Motorcycle Club]] on the \"Holy Fuck\" tour.<ref>[http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/46102-a-place-to-bury-strangers-open-for-brmc] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115145951/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/46102-a-place-to-bury-strangers-open-for-brmc|date=January 15, 2008}}</ref> In April 2008, it was announced that APTBS would open for [[Nine Inch Nails]] on several dates of the latter's US tour. Following several UK gigs, the first album was issued in the UK in October 2008 by [[Rocket Girl]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Maher|first=Dave|title=A Place to Bury Strangers Expand Tour|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/30123-a-place-to-bury-strangers-expand-tour/|website=Pitchfork.com|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> and they received strong praise from the British media including  ''[[NME]]'' and ''[[Kerrang!]]''. In November 2008, the band returned to Europe and the UK on tour supporting [[MGMT]].\n\n===''Exploding Head''===\nIn early 2009, APTBS signed to [[Mute Records]]. The band also announced another European tour and appearances at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]], [[Seaport Music Festival]] and [[Siren Music Festival]].\n\nTheir second album, ''[[Exploding Head]]'', was released by Mute in October 2009.\n\nIn spring 2010, Smith decided to leave APTBS for personal reasons rather than participate in their US tour supporting [[the Big Pink]]. He was replaced for that spring tour by Lunadon, formerly of the bands [[the D4]] and the True Lovers. On July 5, 2010, APTBS visited [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]] for the first time, and played at [[Rock al Parque]], the largest free rock festival in South America.\n\n===''Worship''===\nOn February 14, 2011, Ackermann stated that the band had begun working on their third full-length album.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.rockedition.com/interviews/interview-with-oliver-ackermann-of-a-place-to-bury-strangers |title=Interview with Oliver Ackermann of A Place To Bury Strangers |website=Rockedition.com |date=2011-02-14 |accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref> On January 10, 2012, A Place to Bury Strangers released an all-[[Hipstamatic]] video shot on an [[iPhone]] for the song \"So Far Away\" from the ''Onwards to the Wall'' EP. On February 12, 2012, the band announced that Robi Gonzalez had replaced Weilmeister as drummer.<ref>{{cite web|title=School of Seven Bells Remix A Place To Bury Strangers|url=http://deadoceans.com/blog/2012/02/school-of-seven-bells-remix-a-place-to-bury-strangers/|publisher=Dead Oceans|access-date=2012-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511050055/http://deadoceans.com/blog/2012/02/school-of-seven-bells-remix-a-place-to-bury-strangers/|archive-date=2012-05-11|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> On May 2, 2012, it was announced that the band's third album, ''[[Worship (A Place to Bury Strangers album)|Worship]]'', was scheduled for release on the [[Dead Oceans]] label, on June 11 in the UK and Europe and on June 26, 2012 in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/45996-a-place-to-bury-strangers-announce-new-album |title=A Place to Bury Strangers Announce New Album &#124; News |website=Pitchfork.com |date=2012-04-02 |accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref> The band announced plans to support the release with a full North American tour in October 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. Tour |url=http://aptbs.tumblr.com/ustourdates/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121130070353/http://aptbs.tumblr.com/ustourdates/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-11-30 |publisher=APTBS |accessdate=2015-03-26 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===''Strange Moon'' and ''Transfixiation''===\nIn early March 2013, APTBS announced that they had recorded covers of songs by [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] band [[Dead Moon]] for release on [[Record Store Day]] 2013 as an EP titled ''Strange Moon''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadoceans.com/blog/2013/03/aptbs-announce-tour-dates-with-japandroids-set-to-release-dead-moon-covers-ep-for-rsd/ |title=APTBS Announce Tour Dates with Japandroids, Set to Release Dead Moon Covers EP for RSD News |publisher=Dead Oceans |date=2013-03-06 |accessdate=2015-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324024120/http://deadoceans.com/blog/2013/03/aptbs-announce-tour-dates-with-japandroids-set-to-release-dead-moon-covers-ep-for-rsd/ |archive-date=2015-03-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Gonzalez decided to retire from touring, and during the subsequent 2016 tour, John Fedowitz (Skywave, Ceremony) played drums for the band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/aplacetoburystrangers/photos/a.334259118246/10153482309508247/?type=3|title=A Place To Bury Strangers|website=Facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, the band began recording their fourth studio album, ''Transfixiation''. They recorded for several days at ABC Studios in [[Etne]], [[Norway]], with [[Emil Nikolaisen]] of [[Serena Maneesh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=no&tl=en&js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&eotf=1&u=http%3A%2F%2Fgaffa.com%2Fartikkel%2F70113&authuser=0 |title=Google Translate |website=Translate.google.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-26}}</ref> The album was released on February 17, 2015 on Dead Oceans.\n\n===''Pinned''===\nIn February 2018, the band announced that Lia Simon Braswell would be a permanent replacement for Gonzalez as the band's drummer.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Place to Bury Strangers Release New Single \"Never Coming Back\"|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/01/a-place-to-bury-strangers-new-album-pinned-never-coming-back-stream/|website=Spin|accessdate=23 February 2018|date=31 January 2018}}</ref> Their fifth studio album, ''Pinned'', was released on April 13.\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[A Place to Bury Strangers (album)|A Place to Bury Strangers]]'' (2007, Killer Pimp)\n* ''[[Exploding Head]]'' (2009, [[Mute Records]])\n* ''[[Worship (A Place to Bury Strangers album)|Worship]]'' (2012, [[Dead Oceans]])\n* ''Transfixiation'' (2015, Dead Oceans)\n* ''Pinned'' (2018, Dead Oceans)\n\n===EPs===\n* ''Breathe'' (2006, self-released)\n* ''Missing You'' (2006, self-released)\n* ''Never Going Down'' (2006, self-released)\n* ''The Box Set'' (2008, Vacancy Records)\n* ''Hoxton Square Sessions'' (2009, Mute Records)\n* ''Ego Death 2010 Tour EP'' (2010, Mute Records)\n* ''[[Onwards to the Wall]]'' (2012, Dead Oceans)\n* ''Strange Moon'' (2013, Dead Oceans)\n\n===Singles===\n* \"To Fix the Gash in Your Head\" 10\"/12\" (2008, Meal Deal Records)\n* \"I Know I'll See You\" 7\" (2008, Rocket Girl/Vacancy Records)\n* \"Breathe\" 7\" (2008, Vacancy Records)\n* \"Missing You\" 7\" (2008, Rocket Girl/Vacancy Records)\n* \"[[In Your Heart]]\" 7\" (2009, Mute Records)\n* \"Keep Slipping Away\" 7\" (2009, Mute Records)\n* \"You Are the One\" 7\" (2012, Dead Oceans)\n* \"And I'm Up\" 7\" (2012, Dead Oceans)\n* ''Less Artists More Condos Series #1'' split single with Ceremony (2012, Famous Class)\n* \"Raiser\" 7\" (2013, Sweet Mistakes Productions)\n* \"We've Come So Far\" 7\" (2015, self-released)\n* \"Straight\" 7\" (2015, self-released)\n* \"Never Coming Back\" (2018, Dead Oceans)\n* \"There's Only One of Us\" (2018, Dead Oceans)\n\n===Live albums===\n* ''Loud and Live in 2012'' (2013, self-released)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://aplacetoburystrangers.bandcamp.com/}}\n\n{{A Place to Bury Strangers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Place To Bury Strangers}}\n[[Category:American noise rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Indie rock musical groups from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:Mute Records artists]]\n[[Category:Post-punk revival music groups]]\n[[Category:Shoegazing musical groups]]\n[[Category:Dead Oceans artists]]\n[[Category:Rocket Girl artists]]\n", "name_user": "Weedwhacker128", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePinned:c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Place_to_Bury_Strangers"}
{"title_page": "Barbara Lewis King", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{peacock|date=September 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2017}}\n{{notability|date=May 2017}}\n}}\n'''Barbara Lewis King''' is a bishop of the International New Thought Christian Movement of Churches. She is also the founder of Hillside International Chapel and Truth Center.\n\n== Biography ==\n\nBarbara Lewis King was born in [[Houston, Texas]], to parents Mildred Jackson Shackelford and Lec Andrew Lewis. She was raised by paternal grandmother, Ida Bates Lewis. At 13, she felt a calling to ministry when she volunteered as a Sunday school teacher.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2191863671.html|title=Reverend Dr. Barbara King|last=|first=|date=7 October 2010|work=Los Angeles Sentinel|access-date=8 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118014918/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2191863671.html|archive-date=2018-11-18|url-status = dead|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> At 15, she became a Woman's Day speaker in history at Houston's [[Antioch Missionary Baptist Church|Antioch Baptist Church]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe is married, with one son, Michael, whom she had despite doctors' prognosis that she could not have children because of a disease that she had had. She also mothers a young woman from [[Ghana]], and is the grandmother of five and great-grandmother of three.\n\nKing earned a BA in sociology from [[Texas Southern University]] and a Masters in social work at [[Clark Atlanta University|Atlanta University]]\u2019s School of Social Work.<ref name=\"REVEREND DR. BARBARA L. KING\">{{cite web|title=REVEREND DR. BARBARA L. KING|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/reverend-dr-barbara-l-king|website=The History Makers|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref>\nShe also obtained a Doctor of Ministry from the Ecumenical Theological Seminary of Detroit, Michigan in 2012.<ref name=\"hillsidechapel.org\">{{cite web|title=About Bishop Dr. Barbara Lewis King|url=http://www.hillsidechapel.org/bkbio.html|website=Hillside Chapel|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter obtaining her Masters, King moved to Chicago and worked as a social work administrator, leading the city\u2019s public housing outreach program. There, she met Rev. [[Johnnie Colemon]], the first female African American minister she had met thus far, and was inspired to redirect her path to ministry. King then worked as the director of administration of Christ Universal Temple, Rev. Colemon\u2019s church,<ref name=\"hillsidechapel.org\"/> and was mentored by her throughout her ministerial training in New Thought and Traditional Though at Missouri\u2019s Unity Institute of Continuing Education and the Baptist Training School in Chicago. Following her training, she was ordained twice, by Rev. Roy Blake and then by Rev. Colemon.\n\nShe then became a professor of social work at [[Clark Atlanta University]], and then the dean of students at [[Spelman College]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=4 July 2005|title=Noted Atlanta Minister Barbara Lewis King Weds Philadelphia's SELF, Inc. Founder Dr. Sylvester Outley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbYDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA30&dq=%22barbara%20lewis%20king%22&pg=PA32#v=onepage&q=%22barbara%20lewis%20king%22&f=false|journal=JET|volume=|pages=32|via=}}</ref> She started a Bible study group with 12 members, which grew to become Hillside Chapel and Truth Center. In 1971 she founded the Hillside Chapel and Truth Center.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Hillside Chapel is non-denominational and serves around 5,000 people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-22656346.html|title=Program on South Africa to Celebrate End of Apartheid|last=|first=|date=19 November 1994|work=The Buffalo News|access-date=8 June 2017|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam Research}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, King was named the Development Chief off the Assin Nsuta village in Ghana, West Africa, an area with historic routes in the Slave Route Site. She is the first woman to be ordained as a chief in the region.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=ABOUT DR. BARBARA KING|url=http://www.barbarakingcollection.com/barbara-king.html|website=Barbara King Collection}}</ref> Her stool name is Nana Yaa Twunmwaa I.<ref name=\"hillsidechapel.org\"/>\n\nKing is the first Bishop in the International New Thought Christian Movement. She is committed to \u201c[transforming] lives by practicing and demonstrating the teachings of Jesus The Christ\u201d. She has taught and ministered in Finland, Russia, England, Canada, Israel, Egypt, Kenya, Senegal, South Africa, the Caribbean, Brazil, British Gyuana, and Australia. She led the formation of Hillside Fountain, a South African sister church to her Atlanta church.<ref name=\"REVEREND DR. BARBARA L. KING\"/>\nShe was ordained the first New Thought minister in South Africa and has joined the Sisters of the Boa Morte in Brazail, African origin nuns who were prohibited from serving the traditional church. In 2010, she became the first bishop of the New Thought Christian Movement of Churches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2192860551.html|title=Barbara King Named Bishop|last=|first=|date=14 October 2010|work=Jackson Advocate|access-date=8 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118014929/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2192860551.html|archive-date=2018-11-18|url-status = dead|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref>\n\nShe has been a guest lecturer at Harvard Divinity School Summer Institute for Ministers, and has also been involved with Association of Global New Thought, Concerned Black Clergy of Metropolitan Atlanta, Regional Council of Churches, the American Jewish Committee, Life Members of the NAACP, Academy of Certified Social Workers, National Association of Social Workers, Life Member of the National Council of Negro Women, the National Women's Law Center, Chaplain of the City of Atlanta Police Department, and the Mayoral Appointee to the Ethics Board of Metro Atlanta.\n\n== Honors ==\n* The International New Thought Alliance (INTA) Life Achievement Award\n*The Ernest Holmes Religious Science Award\n*Unity's The Light of God Expressing Award\n*International Civil Rights Walk of Fame, for her work in Dr. Martin Luther King's Chicago movement\n* No. 8 on Savoy Magazine's Power Issue of 100 Most Influential Blacks in America in 2008\n* Beautiful Are Their Feet Honoree \n*International Hall of Honor at Martin Luther King Jr. International Chapel at Morehouse College\n\n== Works ==\n*''Transform Your Life''<ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Barbara|title=Transform Your Life|date=2016|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform}}</ref>\n*''Major contributor to A New Thought for A New Millennium and Wake Up \u2026 Live the Life You Love in Spirit''\n*''In Me, As Me: Ten Principles for Finding the Divine Within and Leave With Love: A Spiritual Guide to Succession Planning''\n*''Piddlin\u2019 For the Soul'' <ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Barbara|title=Piddlin' For the Soul|date=2001|publisher=Barbara King}}</ref>\n*''How to Have Flood and Not Drown: Essays on Stress-Free Living'' <ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Barbara|title=How to Have Flood and Not Drown: Essays on Stress-Free Living|date=1990|publisher=Devorss & Co}}</ref>\n*''The Church: A Matter of Consciousness''\n*''What is a Miracle?''<ref>{{cite book|last1=King-Blake|first1=Barbara|title=What is a Miracle?|publisher=CSA Press}}</ref>\n*''Prosperity that Can\u2019t Quit''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis King, Barbara}}\n[[Category:People from Houston]]\n[[Category:Clark Atlanta University faculty]]\n[[Category:Texas Southern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Atlanta University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{peacock|date=September 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2017}}\n{{notability|date=May 2017}}\n}}\n'''Barbara Lewis King''' is a bishop of the International New Thought Christian Movement of Churches. She is also the founder of Hillside International Chapel and Truth Center.\n\n== Biography ==\n\nBarbara Lewis King was born in [[Houston, Texas]], to parents Mildred Jackson Shackelford and Lec Andrew Lewis. She was raised by paternal grandmother, Ida Bates Lewis. At 13, she felt a calling to ministry when she volunteered as a Sunday school teacher.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2191863671.html|title=Reverend Dr. Barbara King|last=|first=|date=7 October 2010|work=Los Angeles Sentinel|access-date=8 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118014918/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2191863671.html|archive-date=2018-11-18|url-status = dead|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> At 15, she became a Woman's Day speaker in history at Houston's [[Antioch Missionary Baptist Church|Antioch Baptist Church]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe is married, with one son, Michael, whom she had despite doctors' prognosis that she could not have children because of a disease that she had had. She also mothers a young woman from [[Ghana]], and is the grandmother of five and great-grandmother of three.\n\nKing earned a BA in sociology from [[Texas Southern University]] and a Masters in social work at [[Clark Atlanta University|Atlanta University]]\u2019s School of Social Work.<ref name=\"REVEREND DR. BARBARA L. KING\">{{cite web|title=REVEREND DR. BARBARA L. KING|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/reverend-dr-barbara-l-king|website=The History Makers|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref>\nShe also obtained a Doctor of Ministry from the Ecumenical Theological Seminary of Detroit, Michigan in 2012.<ref name=\"hillsidechapel.org\">{{cite web|title=About Bishop Dr. Barbara Lewis King|url=http://www.hillsidechapel.org/bkbio.html|website=Hillside Chapel|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter obtaining her Masters, King moved to Chicago and worked as a social work administrator, leading the city\u2019s public housing outreach program. There, she met Rev. [[Johnnie Colemon]], the first female African American minister she had met thus far, and was inspired to redirect her path to ministry. King then worked as the director of administration of Christ Universal Temple, Rev. Colemon\u2019s church,<ref name=\"hillsidechapel.org\"/> and was mentored by her throughout her ministerial training in New Thought and Traditional Though at Missouri\u2019s Unity Institute of Continuing Education and the Baptist Training School in Chicago. Following her training, she was ordained twice, by Rev. Roy Blake and then by Rev. Colemon.\n\nShe then became a professor of social work at [[Clark Atlanta University]], and then the dean of students at [[Spelman College]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=4 July 2005|title=Noted Atlanta Minister Barbara Lewis King Weds Philadelphia's SELF, Inc. Founder Dr. Sylvester Outley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbYDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA30&dq=%22barbara%20lewis%20king%22&pg=PA32#v=onepage&q=%22barbara%20lewis%20king%22&f=false|journal=JET|volume=|pages=32|via=}}</ref> She started a Bible study group with 12 members, which grew to become Hillside Chapel and Truth Center. In 1971 she founded the Hillside Chapel and Truth Center.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Hillside Chapel is non-demoninational and serves around 5,000 people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-22656346.html|title=Program on South Africa to Celebrate End of Apartheid|last=|first=|date=19 November 1994|work=The Buffalo News|access-date=8 June 2017|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam Research}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, King was named the Development Chief off the Assin Nsuta village in Ghana, West Africa, an area with historic routes in the Slave Route Site. She is the first woman to be ordained as a chief in the region.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=ABOUT DR. BARBARA KING|url=http://www.barbarakingcollection.com/barbara-king.html|website=Barbara King Collection}}</ref> Her stool name is Nana Yaa Twunmwaa I.<ref name=\"hillsidechapel.org\"/>\n\nKing is the first Bishop in the International New Thought Christian Movement. She is committed to \u201c[transforming] lives by practicing and demonstrating the teachings of Jesus The Christ\u201d. She has taught and ministered in Finland, Russia, England, Canada, Israel, Egypt, Kenya, Senegal, South Africa, the Caribbean, Brazil, British Gyuana, and Australia. She led the formation of Hillside Fountain, a South African sister church to her Atlanta church.<ref name=\"REVEREND DR. BARBARA L. KING\"/>\nShe was ordained the first New Thought minister in South Africa and has joined the Sisters of the Boa Morte in Brazail, African origin nuns who were prohibited from serving the traditional church. In 2010, she became the first bishop of the New Thought Christian Movement of Churches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2192860551.html|title=Barbara King Named Bishop|last=|first=|date=14 October 2010|work=Jackson Advocate|access-date=8 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118014929/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2192860551.html|archive-date=2018-11-18|url-status = dead|url-access=subscription |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref>\n\nShe has been a guest lecturer at Harvard Divinity School Summer Institute for Ministers, and has also been involved with Association of Global New Thought, Concerned Black Clergy of Metropolitan Atlanta, Regional Council of Churches, the American Jewish Committee, Life Members of the NAACP, Academy of Certified Social Workers, National Association of Social Workers, Life Member of the National Council of Negro Women, the National Women's Law Center, Chaplain of the City of Atlanta Police Department, and the Mayoral Appointee to the Ethics Board of Metro Atlanta.\n\n== Honors ==\n* The International New Thought Alliance (INTA) Life Achievement Award\n*The Ernest Holmes Religious Science Award\n*Unity's The Light of God Expressing Award\n*International Civil Rights Walk of Fame, for her work in Dr. Martin Luther King's Chicago movement\n* No. 8 on Savoy Magazine's Power Issue of 100 Most Influential Blacks in America in 2008\n* Beautiful Are Their Feet Honoree \n*International Hall of Honor at Martin Luther King Jr. International Chapel at Morehouse College\n\n== Works ==\n*''Transform Your Life''<ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Barbara|title=Transform Your Life|date=2016|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform}}</ref>\n*''Major contributor to A New Thought for A New Millennium and Wake Up \u2026 Live the Life You Love in Spirit''\n*''In Me, As Me: Ten Principles for Finding the Divine Within and Leave With Love: A Spiritual Guide to Succession Planning''\n*''Piddlin\u2019 For the Soul'' <ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Barbara|title=Piddlin' For the Soul|date=2001|publisher=Barbara King}}</ref>\n*''How to Have Flood and Not Drown: Essays on Stress-Free Living'' <ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Barbara|title=How to Have Flood and Not Drown: Essays on Stress-Free Living|date=1990|publisher=Devorss & Co}}</ref>\n*''The Church: A Matter of Consciousness''\n*''What is a Miracle?''<ref>{{cite book|last1=King-Blake|first1=Barbara|title=What is a Miracle?|publisher=CSA Press}}</ref>\n*''Prosperity that Can\u2019t Quit''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis King, Barbara}}\n[[Category:People from Houston]]\n[[Category:Clark Atlanta University faculty]]\n[[Category:Texas Southern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Atlanta University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbara_Lewis_King"}
